</ul><h1>Dog-gone Good For Them</h1><p>Okay, so in terms of whether or not you should buy these, it comes down to two questions:</p>
<ol>
<li>Do dogs like them?</li>
</ol>
<p>And…</p>
<ol start="2">
<li>Do they actually help with hip and joint issues?</li>
</ol>
<p>Also, to be clear, since these are dogs we’re talking about, the answer to question 2 does rely on the answer to question 1.</p>
<p>We, as humans, will generally take our medicine. Something promises a hefty dose of vitamin C or electrolytes or caffeine or dextromethorphan and guaifenesin, we’ll plug our nose and swallow if we have to. But dogs? You could offer them a tablet capable of restoring them to energetic, healthy puppies, but if it tastes unappealing, they won’t have any part of it.</p>
<p>Luckily, the answer to both questions seems to be: yes.</p>
<p>That’s according to the Amazon reviews of these things, at least, where they earn a 4.4 out of 5 based on more than 4,800 reviews. In fact, the reviews make these things sound downright miraculous.</p>
<p>Here are just a few.</p>
<p>Chip <a href="https://www.amazon.com/gp/customer-reviews/R1GHH6MAK0ZG7M/ref=cm_cr_arp_d_rvw_ttl?ie=UTF8&ASIN=B0DK41YJ9B&tag=mehdown-20">says</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>We purchased this for our Chihuahua to try to get her off of the dog aspirin. It is actually working better after a few days, so well we started giving one to our Schnauzer. Our Schnauzer is actually showing less signs of his age after a few days. This comes highly recommended.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Maddie <a href="https://www.amazon.com/gp/customer-reviews/R3RKHSLGLCSI9T/ref=cm_cr_arp_d_rvw_ttl?ie=UTF8&ASIN=B0DK41YJ9B&tag=mehdown-20">says</a>:</p>
